{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}} {{good article}} {{Infobox military person | name = Ismet Popovac | image = File:Ismet Popovac.jpg | image_size = 175 | alt = a male with a moustache and glasses wearing military uniform | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = 21 August 1943 | death_place = Near [[Trebinje]], [[Independent State of Croatia]] (present-day [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]) | allegiance = {{plainlist | * {{flagicon|Kingdom of Yugoslavia}} [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]] (–1941) * {{flagicon image|Chetniks Flag.svg}} [[Chetniks]] (1941–43) * {{flag|Kingdom of Italy}} (1942–43) }} | serviceyears = 1941–43 | commands = Muslim People's Military Organization | battles = {{tree list}} * [[World War II in Yugoslavia]]: **{{Tree list/final branch}}[[Case White]] {{tree list/end}} }} Dr. '''Ismet Popovac''' (died 21 August 1943) was a Bosnian Muslim{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|p=288}} ([[Bosniaks|Bosniak]]) military commander who led a Muslim [[Chetnik]] militia known as the Muslim People's Military Organization ({{lang-sh|Muslimanska nacionalna vojna organizacija}}, MNVO) in [[Bosnia (region)|Bosnia]] and [[Herzegovina]] during [[World War II]]. A physician and lawyer by profession, he was a member of a cultural society known as ''[[Gajret]]'' prior to the [[Axis invasion of Yugoslavia]] in 1941. He was also the mayor of the town of [[Konjic]] prior to the invasion and was allegedly a candidate for [[Vladko Maček]]'s electoral list, but was left without a job in the Yugoslav state government after the creation of the [[Banovina of Croatia]] in 1939.
In 1941, Popovac joined the Chetnik movement of [[Draža Mihailović]]. As a proponent of Bosnian Muslim collaboration with the Chetniks, he suggested that the Chetniks recruit Muslims into their ranks. In October 1942, he enlisted [[Kingdom of Italy|Italian]] aid in fighting the [[Yugoslav Partisans]], and later visited [[Prozor-Rama|Prozor]] to discourage further bloodshed after a Chetnik massacre took the lives of 543–2,500 Muslim and Croat civilians. In early 1943 he led an attack against a Muslim village, before being killed by either the Partisans, Chetniks, or an assassin in the vicinity of the town of [[Trebinje]] later that year.
==Early life== From the Herzegovinian town of [[Nevesinje]], Ismet Popovac was a physician{{sfn|Redžić|2005|p=143}} and lawyer{{sfn|Tomasevich|1975|p=240}} by profession. He finished medical school in [[Belgrade]] and was a vocal supporter of the [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]] during this time.{{sfn|Košarić|18 August 2013}} Prior to the outbreak of [[World War II]] he was a member of the pro-[[Serbs|Serb]] and pro-monarchy cultural society known as ''[[Gajret]]'', whose members were often persecuted by non-Serbs because of their political inclinations.{{sfn|Hoare|2013|p=41}} Popovac was also the mayor of the Bosnian town of [[Konjic]],{{sfn|Malcolm|1994|p=188}}{{sfn|Hoare|2007|p=270}} and allegedly a candidate for [[Vladko Maček]]'s electoral list, but was left without a job in the state government after the creation of the [[Banovina of Croatia]] in 1939.{{sfn|Hoare|2007|p=270}}
==Joining the Chetniks== On 6 April 1941, [[Axis powers|Axis]] forces [[Invasion of Yugoslavia|invaded]] Yugoslavia. Poorly equipped and poorly trained, the [[Royal Yugoslav Army]] was quickly defeated.{{sfn|Cohen|1996|p=28}} Afterwards, Yugoslavia was dismembered, with Serbia being reduced to its pre-1912 borders and placed under a government of German military occupation.{{sfn|Cohen|1996|p=50}} [[Milan Nedić]], a pre-war politician who was known to have pro-Axis leanings, was then selected by the Germans to lead the collaborationist [[Government of National Salvation]] in the [[Territory of the Military Commander in Serbia]].{{sfn|Singleton|1985|p=182}} Meanwhile, the extreme [[Croat]] nationalist and fascist [[Ante Pavelić]], who had been in exile in [[Benito Mussolini]]'s [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]], was appointed ''[[Poglavnik]]'' (leader) of an [[Ustaše]]-led Croatian state – the [[Independent State of Croatia]] (often called the NDH, from the {{lang-hr|Nezavisna Država Hrvatska}}).{{sfn|Goldstein|1999|p=133}} The NDH combined almost all of modern-day [[Croatia]], all of modern-day [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] and parts of modern-day [[Serbia]] into an "Italian-German quasi-protectorate."{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=272}} NDH authorities, led by the [[Ustaše militia]],{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|pp=397–409}} subsequently implemented genocidal policies against the Serb, [[Jewish]] and [[Romani people|Romani]] population living within the borders of the new state.{{sfn|Hoare|2007|pp=20–24}} As a result, two resistance movements emerged – the royalist and Serb Chetniks, led by [[Colonel]] [[Draža Mihailović]], and the multi-ethnic, [[Communist]] [[Yugoslav Partisans]], led by [[Josip Broz Tito]].{{sfn|Ramet|2006|p=4}}
That year, Popovac and fellow Muslim leader [[Mustafa Pašić]] joined the Chetniks.{{sfn|Hoare|2007|p=270}} Popovac hoped to achieve independence for Bosnia and Herzegovina through his cooperation{{sfn|Burgwyn|2005|p=180}} and, according to one Serb Chetnik, his "main goal was to protect the Muslims, rather than to struggle for the Serb nation and Serb affairs."{{sfn|Hoare|2007|p=270}} He later wrote to Mihailović, suggesting that [[Bosnian Muslims]] be recruited into the Chetnik ranks.{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|p=137}} This proposal was met with support from pro-Serb, anti-Communist Muslim leaders in several Bosnian towns. However, as more Muslims began joining the Partisans, the Chetniks increasingly began considering Muslims to be their enemies. Chetnik [[Chetniks#Terror tactics and cleansing actions|atrocities]] against Muslim civilians subsequently increased{{sfn|Malcolm|1994|p=188}} in the late spring of 1941. Due to these actions, and due to Muslims, especially those in eastern Bosnia, being branded by the Chetniks as "Turks" and "[[Ustaše]] cronies," the Chetniks found few Muslim recruits.{{sfn|Velkonija|2003|p=167}}
==Muslim People's Military Organization== [[File:Panorama Prozora.JPG|thumb|right|220px|In 1942, Popovac visited the Bosnian town of Prozor to discourage further bloodshed following a Chetnik massacre of Muslim and Croat civilians.]] In late 1942, a Muslim Chetnik militia known as the Muslim People's Military Organization ({{lang-sh|Muslimanska nacionalna vojna organizacija}}, MNVO){{sfn|Christia|2012|p=200}} was formed in Herzegovina{{sfn|Hoare|2007|p=270}} following a meeting between Popovac and [[Bosnian Serb]] Chetnik leaders [[Dobroslav Jevđević]] and [[Petar Baćović]].{{sfn|Hoare|2013|p=49}} The militia was placed under the control of Popovac, [[Fehim Musakadić]] and Mustafa Pašić.{{sfn|Durmanović|15 November 2006}} It was part of a greater Muslim autonomist circle and in September 1942 an assembly of Herzegovinian Muslim notables in Mostar declared: "We Herzegovinians and Bosnians are nobody's property and we recognize the right of nobody to persecute us; so, insofar as our brothers in [[Zagreb]] do not wish to accede to our demands, we shall seek protection of our interests from other big powers from the ranks of our allies."{{sfn|Hoare|2007|p=271}} In October of that year, Popovac enlisted [[Kingdom of Italy|Italian]] aid in fighting the [[Yugoslav Partisans]].{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=494}} This resulted in the establishment of a Bosnian Muslim [[quisling]] force that operated as part of the [[Anti-Communist Volunteer Militia]].{{sfn|Hoare|2007|p=270}} It was reported that Popovac had "won the majority of the Muslims to his purpose" in the [[Mostar]], Konjic, Nevesinje and [[Gacko]] districts.{{sfn|Redžić|2005|p=104}} Eventually, he came to be seen as one of "the principal representatives of the pro-Chetnik Muslim current" in Bosnia.{{sfn|Hoare|2007|p=270}}
That October, during [[Operation Alfa]], a joint Chetnik–Italian attack against the Partisans, the Chetniks massacred 543–2,500 Muslim and Croat civilians in [[Prozor-Rama|Prozor]]. Several days later, Popovac arrived in the town to console the Bosnian Muslim population and to advise the Chetniks there against committing further atrocities.{{sfn|Goldstein|7 November 2012}} While there, he also attempted to convince local Muslims to join the Chetnik ranks, but was unsuccessful due to the extent of Chetnik atrocities against the Muslim population.{{sfn|Dizdar|Sobolevski|1999|p=365}} On 31 December, in face of widespread Muslim opposition to the Chetniks' genocidal nature, Popovac and his MNVO declared a resolution in [[Kalinovik]], vowing allegiance to [[Peter II of Yugoslavia|King Petar II]] and Mihailović, and claiming Bosnian Muslims as "an integral part of [[Serbdom]]" and the MNVO as "part of the Chetnik movement led by Draža Mihailović, Minister of the Army, Navy and Air Forces."{{sfn|Redžić|2005|p=153}}
In January 1943, Popovac led an attack which resulted in the capture of a Muslim village that was guarded by a large force of Muslim volunteers.{{sfn|Malcolm|1994|pp=188 & 309}} That same month more Chetnik massacres against Bosnian Muslims were carried out, especially in east Bosnia in the areas of [[Koraj]], [[Bijeljina]], [[Srebrenica]], [[Višegrad]], [[Foča]], [[Goražde]], [[Vlasenica]], and around the [[Drina]] river.{{sfn|Redžić|2005|p=154}} His militia cooperated with Chetnik units in fighting the Partisans during the Axis-led [[Case White]] operation in January to March 1943, but did not distinguish itself.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=494}} During the operation itself Chetniks continued their efforts to exterminate the Muslims. Nonetheless, Popovac and Pašić continued seeking Muslim recruits. They declared in their "Address to the Brethren Muslims of Čajniče and Other Nearby Districts" that the main goal of the Chetniks was "the intelligent and honest protection of Muslim interests" and "securing a safe future for our people with the highest principles of [[Islam]]: freedom of religion, holiness of the family, respect for private property, social justice, and democratic political freedom." Furthermore, they dismissed the claim that Muslims were collectively responsible for Ustaše crimes and said "Muslims are bound to the brethren of the [[Orthodox Christianity|Orthodox]] religion by blood and land."{{sfn|Redžić|2005|p=154}}
==Death and legacy== Popovac was killed on 21 August 1943.{{sfn|Gobetti|2007|p=165}} Sources vary on the circumstances of his death. Historian [[Marko Attila Hoare]] states that he was killed by members of the Partisan 10th Herzegovinian Brigade,{{sfn|Hoare|2013|p=51}} Professor [[Jozo Tomasevich]] writes that he was killed by an assassin{{sfn|Tomasevich|1975|p=240}}{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=494}} and Zdravko Dizdar and Mihael Sobolevski claim that he was killed by the Chetniks in the vicinity of [[Trebinje]] after objecting to the killing of Muslims.{{sfn|Dizdar|Sobolevski|1999|p=365}}
By December 1943, it is estimated that 4,000 of Mihailović's Chetniks were Bosnian Muslims. This number accounted for eight percent of all of Mihailović's soldiers.{{sfn|Malcolm|1994|p=188}} In 1944, Mihailović appealed to the Muslims to fight against the Communists, citing the example of Popovac and other Muslim Chetniks.{{sfn|Radan|Pavković|1997|p=221}}
